cedar:
// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: AIR-03 ("gasless claim" that is
// actually a permit/approve phishing an ALREADY-HELD token out of the wallet).
//
// METHOD-BACKED state read (Aggregator type 9; sv = COV). A genuine claim
// receives a future airdrop; a drainer disguises an approval over a token the
// wallet ALREADY holds. The claimed/permit token is normalised to a `TokenKey`
// and tested for membership in `WalletState.tokens` — durable wallet state, not
// an action field. The `claim.source_held_state` reducer fact emits
// `tokenAlreadyHeld`, projected into `context.custom.permitTokenIsHeld` (Bool).
// Defined-not-wired → `optional`, so its absence fail-opens until the sim-server
// fact host serves it. Deny when the permit/claim token is already held (you are
// being drained, not airdropped).
@id("air-permit-on-held-token-deny")
@severity("deny")
@reason("This 'claim' would grant approval over a token you already hold — a draining permit, not an airdrop")
forbid(principal, action == Airdrop::Action::"Claim", resource)
when {
  context has custom
  && context.custom has permitTokenIsHeld
  && context.custom.permitTokenIsHeld
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: AIR-01 (airdrop claim whose
// recipient is an address other than mine — eligibility is mine but the tokens
// go to the attacker).
//
// PURE ACTION-FIELD (Aggregator type 5 — Set-Membership / identity, no
// enrichment). A normal claim pays the eligible holder (self); a malicious
// claim page pre-fills `recipient` with an attacker address. `recipient` is a
// non-optional base `String` field of `Airdrop::ClaimContext`, and "self" is
// the evaluated wallet's address — `principal.address` (the `Wallet` entity's
// `address`). Cedar compares the two directly, so this manifest declares NO
// `policy_rpc` and NO `custom_context`. Deny when the recipient is not self.
// Both sides are lowercase-hex normalised by the lowering.
@id("air-recipient-not-self-deny")
@severity("deny")
@reason("This airdrop claim pays out to an address that is not your wallet")
forbid(principal, action == Airdrop::Action::"Claim", resource)
when {
  context.recipient != principal.address
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: AMMLP-1 (remove_liquidity output
// redirected to an address other than the signer).
//
// Phishing UIs swap one field — `recipient` — for the attacker on LP exit, a
// flow the swap-output guard (UNI-01) does not cover. `recipient` lives at
// `params.recipient` for the `pooled_burn` variant (an OPTIONAL nested String;
// the V3 variants send to the NFT owner and carry no recipient field), so this
// `has`-guards the nested path then compares it to `principal.address`. Both are
// lowercase hex Strings — exact equality holds — with NO enrichment (sv = COV).
@id("ammlp-remove-recipient-not-self-deny")
@severity("deny")
@reason("This liquidity withdrawal sends the funds to an address that is not your wallet")
forbid(principal, action == Amm::Action::"RemoveLiquidity", resource)
when {
  context.params has recipient
  && context.params.recipient != principal.address
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: BRG-01 (bridge sends to a
// recipient that is not the user's own wallet).
//
// Address-poisoning is the single highest-loss path in bridging ($68M WBTC in
// one case): the destination/recipient sits as a separate calldata argument the
// user rarely scrutinises, so a look-alike address is easy to miss. A bridge
// move that has no dedicated decode lands as `Token::Erc20Transfer`, where the
// destination is the parsed, COMPARABLE String field `context.recipient` and
// the actor's own address is `principal.address` (Core::Wallet entity attr).
//
// `dest_is_self` is therefore a pure action-field comparison — `recipient`
// equals the wallet address — needing NO enrichment / policy_rpc call: Cedar
// compares the two Strings for equality directly. The manifest stays pure
// ({id, schema_version, trigger}). Deny when the recipient is NOT the wallet.
//
// Addresses are lowercase hex on both sides (lowering normalizes), so `==`
// is a sound identity test here.
@id("bridge-recipient-not-self-deny")
@severity("deny")
@reason("Bridge recipient is not your own wallet address — likely address poisoning")
forbid(principal, action == Token::Action::"Erc20Transfer", resource)
when {
  context.recipient != principal.address
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: BRG-12 (bridge refund / recovery
// address is not the user's own wallet).
//
// On a failed fill or unreceivable destination, funds return to the bridge's
// refund / recovery address. That fallback address is a SEPARATE calldata
// argument the user almost never inspects — if it is an attacker address or a
// contract that cannot receive a refund, a failed transfer becomes a permanent
// loss. With no dedicated bridge decode the call lands as `Core::Unknown`:
// `refundAddress` is buried in the `calldata` hex String, distinct from
// `recipient`, so BRG-01's `recipient`-vs-self logic does NOT cover it and Cedar
// cannot extract it. This is a METHOD: `bridge.refund_self` introspects the
// calldata for the refund/recovery address and compares it to the wallet owner,
// emitting the Bool `refundNotSelf` (true = refund address is not the wallet).
//
// Distinct from BRG-01 (the success-path recipient): this is the failure-path
// fallback, invisible on a normal trade. `custom` / field are optional; the call
// is `optional` and fail-opens until the refund-introspection surface ships.
// Deny when the refund address is not the wallet.
@id("bridge-refund-not-self-warn")
@severity("warn")
@reason("Bridge refund address is not your wallet — a failed transfer would be unrecoverable")
forbid(principal, action == Core::Action::"Unknown", resource)
when {
  context has custom
  && context.custom has refundNotSelf
  && context.custom.refundNotSelf
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: BRG-02 (funds sent to a bridge
// contract that is not on the known-good bridge allowlist).
//
// Fake bridge sites are a top bridging loss path ($520K LINK to a spoofed
// bridge; Stargate / Across UI impersonation is common). A bridge move with no
// dedicated decode lands as `Core::Unknown` with the destination contract as
// the parsed, COMPARABLE String field `context.target`. The control is a
// literal SET-MEMBERSHIP test: deny when `target` is NOT among the known-good
// bridge contracts — no enrichment / policy_rpc call is needed because the
// allowlist is config inlined as a Cedar set literal (design proposal F#2 —
// personalized / registry-backed supply via a Set<String> custom field is a
// later increment). The manifest stays pure ({id, schema_version, trigger}).
//
// Addresses are lowercase hex (lowering normalizes); the sample entries below
// are canonical mainnet bridge routers (Stargate, Across SpokePool, CCTP
// TokenMessenger). Unmatched Unknown calldata is also caught by the generic
// blind-sign warning (GEN-09), so a registry miss never silently passes.
@id("bridge-target-not-allowlisted-deny")
@severity("deny")
@reason("Bridge contract is not on the known-good bridge allowlist — possible fake bridge")
forbid(principal, action == Core::Action::"Unknown", resource)
when {
  !([
    "0x8731d54e9d02c286767d56ac03e8037c07e01e98",
    "0x5c7bcd6e7de5423a257d81b442095a1a6ced35c5",
    "0xbd3fa81b58ba92a82136038b25adec7066af3155"
  ].contains(context.target))
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: BRG-03 (unlimited / over-balance
// ERC20 approval to a bridge contract — only a finite, ~bridge-amount approval
// is acceptable).
//
// In the LI.FI exploit (2024-07, ~$11.6M) only wallets holding an UNLIMITED
// approval to the bridge were drained; wallets with a finite approval were
// unharmed. This is the bridge instance of GEN-01: the approve lands as
// `Token::Erc20Approve` with `amount` a raw U256 hex String, so "unlimited"
// CANNOT be tested in Cedar directly — it cannot compare a hex String
// numerically. The unlimited verdict is supplied as the enriched Bool
// `approvalIsUnlimited`, projected into `context.custom` by the REUSED
// `approval.unlimited_over_balance` policy_rpc call (sim-server wallet-state
// read of approval shape vs available balance). `custom` is optional, so the
// guard `has`-checks the path; the call is `optional` and fail-opens until the
// sim-server fact host ships.
//
// `approvalAmountOverBalance` (decimal) is also projected for over-balance
// scoring; this slice keys the deny on the unlimited flag, leaving the
// amount-far-exceeds-bridge-send threshold to a later increment. Deny applies
// to every spender — an unlimited bridge approval is never the safe default.
@id("bridge-unlimited-approval-deny")
@severity("deny")
@reason("Unlimited token approval to a bridge — a drained bridge could take your full balance")
forbid(principal, action == Token::Action::"Erc20Approve", resource)
when {
  context has custom
  && context.custom has approvalIsUnlimited
  && context.custom.approvalIsUnlimited
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: GEN-08 (gas cost disproportionate
// to the value moved).
//
// A swap whose gas fee is a large fraction of the value it actually moves is
// either dust-attack bait or a mis-priced transaction the user should reconsider.
// The ratio is `gas_usd / action_value_usd` — two USD valuations divided
// (Aggregator type 2 — Valuation, combined). Cedar cannot divide two `decimal`
// values, so the division is done off-Cedar: the manifest's
// `valuation.gas_cost_ratio` policy_rpc call projects the ratio into
// `context.custom.gasCostRatioOfValue`.
//
// `custom` is optional, so the guard `has`-checks the path; the value is a Cedar
// `decimal` extension, so the threshold uses `.greaterThan(...)`. The native +
// input price reads live in the sim-server fact host, so the call is `optional`
// and the policy fail-opens until it ships. The threshold is user configuration;
// for this slice it is inlined (0.2 ⇒ warn when gas exceeds 20% of the swap's
// value).
//
// Scoped to `Amm::Action::"Swap"` because the ratio's denominator (the swap's
// input value) and `gasEstimate` are both swap-context fields today.
@id("gas-cost-ratio-warn")
@severity("warn")
@reason("The gas fee is a large fraction of the value this swap moves")
forbid(principal, action == Amm::Action::"Swap", resource)
when {
  context has custom
  && context.custom has gasCostRatioOfValue
  && context.custom.gasCostRatioOfValue.greaterThan(decimal("0.2000"))
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: GEN-07 (absolute gas cost over a
// USD cap).
//
// An abnormally expensive transaction — fat-fingered gas, a malicious relayer
// padding the fee, or a griefing contract — should be stopped before signing.
// Gas cost in USD is `gasEstimate × native_token price_value` (Aggregator type 2
// — Valuation): the swap's `gasEstimate` is a raw U256 hex String on the base
// context (NOT Cedar-comparable), so the USD product is computed off-Cedar and
// the manifest's `valuation.gas_cost_usd` policy_rpc call projects it into
// `context.custom.gasCostUsd`.
//
// `custom` is optional, so the guard `has`-checks the path; the value is a Cedar
// `decimal` extension, so the threshold uses `.greaterThan(...)`. The native
// price read lives in the sim-server fact host, so the call is `optional` and the
// policy fail-opens until it ships. The cap is user configuration; for this slice
// it is inlined ($150) — personalized supply is a later increment.
//
// Scoped to `Amm::Action::"Swap"` because `gasEstimate` is a base field only of
// the swap context today (the only action carrying the route's gas projection).
@id("gas-cost-usd-cap-deny")
@severity("deny")
@reason("The gas fee for this transaction is abnormally high in USD terms")
forbid(principal, action == Amm::Action::"Swap", resource)
when {
  context has custom
  && context.custom has gasCostUsd
  && context.custom.gasCostUsd.greaterThan(decimal("150.0000"))
};

@id("hl-confirm-approve-agent")
@severity("warn")
@reason("Authorizing an agent wallet to trade on your behalf — confirm before approving")
forbid(
  principal,
  action == HyperliquidCore::Action::"HlApproveAgent",
  resource
);

@id("hl-confirm-high-leverage")
@severity("warn")
@reason("Raising leverage above 20x on Hyperliquid — confirm before applying")
forbid(principal, action == Perp::Action::"ChangeLeverage", resource)
when {
  context.venue.name == "hyperliquid"
    && context.newLeverage.greaterThan(decimal("20.0"))
};

@id("hl-confirm-usd-send")
@severity("warn")
@reason("Sending USDC to another account on Hyperliquid — confirm before sending")
forbid(
  principal,
  action == HyperliquidCore::Action::"HlUsdSend",
  resource
);

@id("hl-confirm-withdraw")
@severity("warn")
@reason("Withdrawing funds off Hyperliquid — confirm before the request is sent")
forbid(
  principal,
  action == HyperliquidCore::Action::"HlWithdraw",
  resource
);

@id("hl-no-short-perp")
@severity("deny")
@reason("Short perp orders on Hyperliquid are blocked by policy")
forbid(principal, action == Perp::Action::"PlaceOrder", resource)
when {
  context.venue.name == "hyperliquid" && context.side == "short" && context.reduceOnly == false
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: GEN-06 (moving too large a share of
// one asset's holding in a single action).
//
// Sending or approving a very large fraction of what you hold of one token is a
// classic drain signature (and an easy fat-finger). The share is
// `amount / token_balance × 100` — the proposed action's `amount` over the
// wallet's CURRENT holding of that exact token (Aggregator type 1 — State read:
// the denominator is `token_holdings.balance_amount`, not the whole portfolio,
// so this is distinct from the portfolio-fold `portfolio.group_pct`). `amount`
// is a raw U256 hex String (NOT Cedar-comparable) and the division needs the
// state balance, so the percentage is computed off-Cedar: the manifest's
// `token.outflow_pct_of_holding` policy_rpc call projects it into
// `context.custom.pctOfHolding`.
//
// `custom` is optional, so the guard `has`-checks the path; the value is a Cedar
// `decimal` extension, so the threshold uses `.greaterThan(...)`. The balance
// read lives in the sim-server fact host, so the call is `optional` and the
// policy fail-opens until it ships. The threshold is user configuration; for this
// slice it is inlined (90 ⇒ warn when over 90% of the holding moves at once).
@id("holding-pct-outflow-warn")
@severity("warn")
@reason("This moves a very large share of your holding of this token in one go")
forbid(principal, action == Token::Action::"Erc20Transfer", resource)
when {
  context has custom
  && context.custom has pctOfHolding
  && context.custom.pctOfHolding.greaterThan(decimal("90.0000"))
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: GEN-15 (`increaseAllowance` stacking
// onto an existing approval).
//
// `increaseAllowance(spender, addedValue)` ADDS to whatever allowance already
// exists, so a small-looking `addedValue` can push the effective allowance far
// past the wallet's balance once the current on-chain allowance is folded in.
// The resulting allowance is `current_allowance (State₁) + addedValue` — a U256
// sum (Aggregator type 1 — State read + reducer). U256 is NOT Cedar-comparable,
// so the result is scored off-Cedar against the wallet balance: the manifest's
// `approval.resulting_allowance_state` policy_rpc call projects the post-increase
// over-balance ratio into `context.custom.resultingAllowanceOverBalance` and the
// unlimited flag into `context.custom.resultingAllowanceUnlimited`.
//
// `custom` is optional, so each branch `has`-checks its field;
// `resultingAllowanceOverBalance` is a `decimal` (use `.greaterThan(...)`),
// `resultingAllowanceUnlimited` is a `Bool`. The state allowance read lives in
// the sim-server fact host, so the call is `optional` and the policy fail-opens
// until it ships. The over-balance threshold is user configuration; for this
// slice it is inlined (5× balance) and OR'd with the unlimited flag.
@id("increase-allowance-cap-warn")
@severity("warn")
@reason("Adding to your existing allowance pushes it well past your balance")
forbid(principal, action == Token::Action::"Erc20Approve", resource)
when {
  context has custom
  && (
    (context.custom has resultingAllowanceUnlimited
       && context.custom.resultingAllowanceUnlimited)
    || (context.custom has resultingAllowanceOverBalance
       && context.custom.resultingAllowanceOverBalance.greaterThan(decimal("5.0000")))
  )
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: LP-02 (commit / approve on a
// launchpad platform outside the personal allowlist).
//
// LITERAL SET-MEMBERSHIP. Fake clones of legitimate launchpads (e.g. PinkSale)
// are the real loss path: the user is lured into committing funds on a
// look-alike. This reduces to a destination-allowlist control — "is this a
// platform I authorised?" — so it needs no wallet state (sv = COV).
//
// The allowlist is LOCAL user config kept as a Cedar `Set<String>` literal
// (mirrors the GEN-01 / VALUE / AAVE-05 allowlist pattern), so the manifest
// declares NO `policy_rpc` and NO `custom_context`. The platform is carried as
// `context.platform.name` — the `name` of a `Core::ProtocolRef` — a
// non-optional base `String`. Deny when the platform name is NOT allowlisted.
// Entries below are placeholders for the user's list (protocol slugs, not
// addresses, since `ProtocolRef` is name-based).
@id("lp-commit-platform-allowlist-deny")
@severity("deny")
@reason("Committing to a launchpad platform not on your allowlist is blocked")
forbid(principal, action == Launchpad::Action::"Commit", resource)
when {
  !(["coinlist", "fjord", "pinksale"].contains(context.platform.name))
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: GEN-16 (an approval hidden inside a
// benign-looking bundle).
//
// Drainer bundles wrap a token grant inside an innocuous-looking multicall ("claim
// your reward") so the user sees the friendly outer call and never notices the
// `approve` / `setApprovalForAll` riding along. The reducer projects each child
// `ActionBody` to a flat `Set<MulticallChildSummary>` of `(domain, action)` tags
// on the base context (`context.children`) — Cedar can read that set directly
// (Aggregator type 8 — Decode Introspection), so this is a pure action-shape
// policy with NO `policy_rpc` and NO `custom_context`.
//
// Warn when the bundle contains any token-grant child. Per-child detail
// (spender, amount) is evaluated separately — each child is also dispatched as
// its own envelope — so this policy only needs the (domain, action) shape to flag
// the bundle for a human look.
@id("multicall-hidden-approval-warn")
@severity("warn")
@reason("This bundle quietly includes a token-approval call — check what you are granting")
forbid(principal, action == Core::Action::"Multicall", resource)
when {
  context.children.containsAny([
    { domain: "token", action: "erc20_approve" },
    { domain: "token", action: "permit2_approve" },
    { domain: "token", action: "nft_approve" },
    { domain: "token", action: "nft_set_approval_for_all" }
  ])
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: NFT-05 (unlimited / over-cap WETH
// approval granted to a bidding conduit; the NFT-bid instance of GEN-01).
//
// Bidding on NFTs requires pre-approving WETH to the marketplace conduit. An
// `approve(spender, U256::MAX)` (or an amount far over what a bid needs) turns
// that conduit into an open-ended spend channel. `amount` is a raw U256 hex
// String on `Erc20ApproveContext`, so "unlimited" CANNOT be tested in Cedar
// directly — it arrives as the enriched Bool `bidApprovalIsUnlimited`,
// projected by REUSING the existing `approval.unlimited_over_balance` policy_rpc
// (Aggregator type 1 — Direct State read of `approvals_erc20.is_unlimited` ×
// `token_holdings.balance_amount`). The companion `bidApprovalOverBalance`
// (decimal, approve-amount / available-balance) is also projected for the
// over-cap scoring; this slice keys the warn on the unlimited flag, leaving the
// personalized `bid_weth_cap` threshold to a later increment.
//
// `custom` is optional, so the guard `has`-checks the path before reading it;
// the call is `optional`, so its absence fail-opens until the fact host ships.
@id("nft-bid-weth-unlimited-warn")
@severity("warn")
@reason("this WETH approval is unlimited — a bid only needs the offer amount, so cap it")
forbid(principal, action == Token::Action::"Erc20Approve", resource)
when {
  context has custom
  && context.custom has bidApprovalIsUnlimited
  && context.custom.bidApprovalIsUnlimited
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: NFT-07 (order signature with a very
// distant / effectively open-ended expiry).
//
// A Seaport/Blur listing or offer signature stays exploitable until its
// `deadline`. A signature that lives far past any reasonable listing window is a
// "free option" handed to a counterparty — it can still be filled long after the
// floor has dropped. Warn on such long-lived order signatures (people do use long
// listings deliberately, hence warn, not deny).
//
// This is a pure action-field policy (Aggregator type 8 — Decode Introspection):
// the marketplace order arrives undecoded as `Core::Action::"Unknown"` with an
// `OffchainSig` nature, and the signed expiry is the base context Long
// `context.meta.nature.deadline` (unix seconds, present only on offchain_sig
// natures). No enrichment is required — the manifest declares no policy_rpc and
// no custom_context. `deadline` is optional in the schema (omitted by onchain_tx
// natures), so the body `has`-checks the path before reading it.
//
// The cutoff is an absolute unix-seconds horizon (here 2 000 000 000 ≈ 2033-05),
// well beyond any normal listing window; personalizing it to
// `submittedAt + user.order_max_horizon` needs Cedar Long arithmetic (a later
// enrichment increment), so this slice uses the absolute far-future cutoff.
@id("nft-far-expiry-order-warn")
@severity("warn")
@reason("this order signature does not expire for a very long time — long-lived signatures stay exploitable after the floor drops")
forbid(principal, action == Core::Action::"Unknown", resource)
when {
  context.meta.nature.kind == "offchain_sig"
  && context.meta.nature has deadline
  && context.meta.nature.deadline > 2000000000
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: NFT-04 (setApprovalForAll to an
// off-allowlist conduit/operator; the NFT-marketplace instance of GEN-02).
//
// `setApprovalForAll(operator, true)` is the on-chain precondition that makes a
// zero-price-listing drain *executable*: it hands one operator (a Seaport
// conduit, a Blur exchange, …) the right to move every token in the collection.
// Phishing "free mint" sites always request this first. Warn when collection-
// wide operator rights are granted (`approved == true`) to a `spender` that is
// not a known marketplace conduit.
//
// `spender` and `approved` are base fields of `NftSetApprovalForAllContext`, so
// no enrichment is needed (Aggregator type 5 — Set Membership against a
// literal set). The marketplace-conduit allowlist is user/marketplace
// configuration; for this slice it is inlined as a Cedar set literal
// (personalized supply via a Set<String> custom field is a later increment —
// design proposal F#2). Addresses are lowercase hex; sample entries are the
// OpenSea Seaport 1.1 conduit and the Blur ExecutionDelegate.
@id("nft-setapprovalforall-conduit-warn")
@severity("warn")
@reason("setApprovalForAll grants this operator your entire collection, and it is not a recognized marketplace conduit")
forbid(principal, action == Token::Action::"NftSetApprovalForAll", resource)
when {
  context.approved
  && !([
    "0x1e0049783f008a0085193e00003d00cd54003c71",
    "0x00000000000111abe46ff893f3b2fdf1f759a8a8"
  ].contains(context.spender))
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: NFT-03 (Blur "Root" bulk-listing
// signature whose EIP-712 domain is not the genuine Blur exchange).
//
// Blur lets a single "Root" signature list an entire collection at once; the
// bundled hash is opaque, so the wallet cannot unfold what is being signed
// (SlowMist-confirmed phishing primitive). The defense is provenance: an opaque
// order-signature whose declared EIP-712 domain is not a trusted marketplace
// must be denied — signing something you cannot read, from an unrecognized
// origin, is itself the danger signal (overlaps GEN-09's blind-sign warn, which
// this hardens to a deny for the Blur-Root shape).
//
// The Blur Root cannot be decoded, so it surfaces as `Core::Action::"Unknown"`
// with an `OffchainSig` nature. The signed EIP-712 domain name is the base
// context String `context.meta.nature.domain.name` (Aggregator type 5 — Set
// Membership against a literal allowlist). The trusted-marketplace domain
// allowlist is configuration; for this slice it is inlined as a Cedar set
// literal. `domain` and `domain.name` are optional in the schema (present only
// on offchain_sig natures), so the body `has`-checks the path before reading it.
@id("nft-untrusted-blur-root-deny")
@severity("deny")
@reason("this opaque order signature claims a marketplace domain that is not on the trusted allowlist")
forbid(principal, action == Core::Action::"Unknown", resource)
when {
  context.meta.nature.kind == "offchain_sig"
  && context.meta.nature has domain
  && context.meta.nature.domain has name
  && !(["Blur Exchange", "Seaport"].contains(context.meta.nature.domain.name))
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: GEN-03 (Permit / Permit2 signature
// granting a large allowance or a far-future expiry).
//
// An off-chain `permit` is a gasless allowance: a signature anyone can later
// submit to set a spender's allowance until `deadline`. A large USD allowance or
// a deadline months out is the same drain exposure as an unlimited on-chain
// `approve`, but easier to miss because it never hits a confirmation screen.
//
// Two enriched facts drive this (Aggregator type 2 — Valuation, plus a
// clock-relative horizon):
//   - `permitAllowanceUsd`  — `amount × price_value`. `amount` is a raw U256 hex
//                             String (NOT Cedar-comparable), so the USD product
//                             is computed off-Cedar.
//   - `permitExpiryHorizonSec` — `deadline − now`. The action's `deadline` is a
//                             Long, but the horizon needs the host clock (Cedar
//                             has no `now`), so it is computed off-Cedar.
// The manifest's `permit.allowance_horizon` policy_rpc call emits both fields
// from one call (record output; precedent `approval.unlimited_over_balance`).
//
// `custom` is optional, so each branch `has`-checks its field. `permitAllowanceUsd`
// is a `decimal` (use `.greaterThan(...)`); `permitExpiryHorizonSec` is a `Long`
// (use `>`). The price read lives in the sim-server fact host, so the call is
// `optional` and the policy fail-opens until it ships. Thresholds are user
// configuration; for this slice they are inlined ($10,000 allowance OR a horizon
// over 30 days = 2,592,000 s).
@id("permit-allowance-horizon-warn")
@severity("warn")
@reason("This off-chain permit grants a large allowance or stays valid for a long time")
forbid(principal, action == Token::Action::"Erc20Permit", resource)
when {
  context has custom
  && (
    (context.custom has permitAllowanceUsd
       && context.custom.permitAllowanceUsd.greaterThan(decimal("10000.0000")))
    || (context.custom has permitExpiryHorizonSec
       && context.custom.permitExpiryHorizonSec > 2592000)
  )
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: PERP-01 (leverage above your
// self-set cap).
//
// High leverage thins the distance to liquidation — a brief wick can wipe the
// account (the James Wynn $100M → $900 story). Deny an open whose effective
// leverage exceeds the user's cold-decided cap (10x here, user config).
//
// The order's leverage CANNOT be read in Cedar from the base context: both
// `context.leverage` and `context.size.leverage` (the `leverage_implied`
// SizeSpec arm) are raw `Decimal`-as-String fields, and Cedar cannot compare a
// String numerically. The manifest's `perp.order_leverage` call resolves the
// effective leverage (explicit, or collateral×size-implied) into the enriched
// `decimal` `orderLeverage`. Defined-not-implemented → `optional` (fail-open).
@id("perp-leverage-cap-deny")
@severity("deny")
@reason("This entry's leverage is above the cap you set for yourself")
forbid(principal, action == Perp::Action::"OpenPosition", resource)
when {
  context has custom
  && context.custom has orderLeverage
  && context.custom.orderLeverage.greaterThan(decimal("10.0000"))
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: PERP-11 (raising the leverage on a
// position you already hold).
//
// Bumping leverage on an open position (especially isolated) pulls margin out and
// walks liq_price toward mark — the same move now liquidates sooner. The trigger
// is "a position exists in this market AND newLeverage > current leverage". Both
// the existence check (`PerpPosition.size_base ≠ 0`, State₁) and the current
// leverage (`PerpPosition.leverage`, decimal, State₁) live in wallet state, while
// `context.newLeverage` is a `Decimal`-as-String the action carries — Cedar can't
// compare a String to a state decimal. The manifest's `perp.leverage_increase`
// resolves the position and does the comparison, emitting the `Bool`
// `leverageIncrease`. Defined-not-wired → `optional` (fail-open).
@id("perp-leverage-increase-warn")
@severity("warn")
@reason("Raising leverage on this open position moves its liquidation price closer to the current price")
forbid(principal, action == Perp::Action::"ChangeLeverage", resource)
when {
  context has custom
  && context.custom has leverageIncrease
  && context.custom.leverageIncrease
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: PERP-05 (market order with a loose
// slippage tolerance).
//
// On a thin book or through a liquidation band a market order fills far from
// intent (the classic alt-market fat-finger). The order's own tolerance is the
// signal: `slippageBp` is a base `Long` field of `Perp::OpenPositionContext`, so
// this reads `context.slippageBp` DIRECTLY — no enrichment, no method, no
// custom_context (like `swap-slippage-high-warn`). Warn when the allowed slippage
// is above 100 bp (1%, user config).
@id("perp-market-slippage-warn")
@severity("warn")
@reason("This market order allows a large slippage — it could fill far from the price you expect")
forbid(principal, action == Perp::Action::"OpenPosition", resource)
when { context.slippageBp > 100 };

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: PERP-08 (a "reduce" order that
// overshoots zero and flips into a position on the other side).
//
// Mis-sizing a close/reduce can sail past 0 and open a fresh OPPOSITE position —
// Hyperliquid's infamous "reduce" that became a $100M short. Detecting the
// overshoot needs the CURRENT position's size from wallet state
// (`PerpPosition.size_base`, State₁) compared to the order's decrease size; that
// size is a U256-hex String (not Cedar-comparable) and the current position is
// not in the action context. The manifest's `perp.crosses_zero` does the
// comparison and emits the `Bool` `crossesZero`. Defined-not-wired → `optional`
// (fail-open). Deny outright — a flip is never the intent of a reduce.
@id("perp-reduce-only-flip-deny")
@severity("deny")
@reason("This reduce order is larger than your position — it would flip you to the opposite side")
forbid(principal, action == Perp::Action::"DecreasePosition", resource)
when {
  context has custom
  && context.custom has crossesZero
  && context.custom.crossesZero
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: GEN-20 (re-approving a spender you
// already granted).
//
// Approving a spender you have ALREADY approved is usually redundant, and a
// surprise re-approval prompt (especially right after a fresh grant) is a common
// phishing tell — the dapp is quietly bumping or refreshing an allowance. The
// check is "does a non-zero allowance for `(token, spender)` already exist in
// wallet state?" (Aggregator type 1 — State read: `approvals_erc20.amount > 0`).
// The manifest's `approval.already_granted` policy_rpc call projects the answer
// into `context.custom.alreadyGranted`.
//
// `custom` is optional, so the guard `has`-checks the path; the value is a `Bool`.
// The allowance read lives in the sim-server fact host, so the call is `optional`
// and the policy fail-opens until it ships. This is a low-severity informational
// nudge (warn, not deny).
@id("reapprove-already-granted-warn")
@severity("warn")
@reason("You already have an allowance for this spender — this approval may be redundant")
forbid(principal, action == Token::Action::"Erc20Approve", resource)
when {
  context has custom
  && context.custom has alreadyGranted
  && context.custom.alreadyGranted
};

// pasu default v2 policy — demand signal: irreversible-typo-fatfinger-send
// (Send Safety Set). Coinbase/MetaMask/ENS/Bitdeer all warn that a confirmed
// transfer is irreversible; the most certain way to lose funds permanently is a
// send to the burn / zero address.
//
// `recipient` is a base, non-optional `String` field of
// `Token::Erc20TransferContext` (same shape as swap-recipient-not-self-deny),
// so this judges with NO enrichment and NO policy_rpc — it just compares the
// recipient against the known burn-address literals. Addresses are lowercase
// hex on both sides (host-normalized), so exact String equality / Set membership
// holds. The zero address and 0x…dead have no key holder: a transfer there is
// permanent loss, hence `deny` (a hard block, not a one-beat warn).
//
// NOTE (dedup): the originating signal also bundled a "first-time recipient,
// pause" warn. That half duplicates the existing draft
// transfer-unknown-recipient-warn (same threat, severity, and external history
// Bool) and is intentionally NOT carried here; this policy keeps only the novel
// burn-address clause.
@id("send-first-time-or-burn-recipient-warn")
@severity("deny")
@reason("This send goes to a burn address (0x000…000 / 0x…dead) — funds sent there are permanently lost")
forbid(principal, action == Token::Action::"Erc20Transfer", resource)
when {
  ["0x0000000000000000000000000000000000000000",
   "0x000000000000000000000000000000000000dead"].contains(context.recipient)
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: GEN-02 (setApprovalForAll to a
// non-allowlisted operator).
//
// `setApprovalForAll(operator, true)` hands an operator the right to move every
// token in a collection with a single signature — the standard NFT-drain
// primitive. Warn when collection-wide operator rights are granted
// (`approved == true`) to a `spender` outside the user's operator allowlist.
//
// `spender` and `approved` are base fields of `NftSetApprovalForAllContext`, so
// no enrichment is required (Aggregator type 5 — Set Membership, evaluated
// against a literal set). The allowlist is user configuration; for this slice
// it is inlined as a Cedar set literal (design proposal F#2 — personalized
// supply via enrichment/Set<String> custom field is a later increment). Sample
// entry below is the OpenSea Seaport conduit; addresses are lowercase hex.
@id("setapprovalforall-operator-warning")
@severity("warn")
@reason("setApprovalForAll grants this operator your entire collection — it is not in your allowlist")
forbid(principal, action == Token::Action::"NftSetApprovalForAll", resource)
when {
  context.approved
  && !(["0x1e0049783f008a0085193e00003d00cd54003c71"].contains(context.spender))
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: GEN-17 (signature whose chainId is
// not the chain you are connected to).
//
// An EIP-712 signature carries the chainId it is bound to in its domain. When
// that chainId differs from the chain the wallet is currently connected to, the
// signature is being requested for a DIFFERENT chain — a cross-chain replay /
// confusion vector (sign once "for Polygon", get it replayed on mainnet).
//
// The verdict is `domain.chainId != connected_chain`. The action carries
// `meta.nature.domain.chainId` (a Long), but the "connected chain" is the
// evaluation context's chain, which is NOT a field of the action context — only
// the fact host holds both sides. So the comparison is made off-Cedar
// (Aggregator type 9 — host-side context): the manifest's
// `signature.chain_mismatch` policy_rpc call projects the verdict into
// `context.custom.chainMismatch`.
//
// `custom` is optional, so the guard `has`-checks the path; the value is a `Bool`.
// The eval-chain comparison runs in the sim-server fact host, so the call is
// `optional` and the policy fail-opens until it ships. Scoped to
// `Token::Action::"Erc20Permit"` — an off-chain signature action that carries an
// EIP-712 domain.
@id("signature-chain-mismatch-permit-warn")
@severity("warn")
@reason("This signature is bound to a different chain than the one you are connected to")
forbid(principal, action == Token::Action::"Erc20Permit", resource)
when {
  context has custom
  && context.custom has chainMismatch
  && context.custom.chainMismatch
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: UNI-01 (swap output redirected to
// an address other than the signer).
//
// Drainers dress a swap up as normal but flip only `recipient` to the attacker:
// you sell your tokens and someone else receives the proceeds. `recipient` is a
// base `String` field of `Amm::SwapContext` and `principal.address` is the
// evaluated wallet's address (Wallet entity attr) — both non-optional Strings —
// so this compares directly with NO enrichment and NO policy_rpc (sv = COV).
// Addresses are lowercase hex on both sides, so exact String equality holds.
@id("swap-recipient-not-self-deny")
@severity("deny")
@reason("This swap sends the bought tokens to an address that is not your wallet")
forbid(principal, action == Amm::Action::"Swap", resource)
when { context.recipient != principal.address };

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: UNI-02 (slippage tolerance set far
// too wide → sandwich-MEV bait).
//
// A wide slippage band lets an MEV bot push the price out and back within that
// band (the canonical sandwich; a documented $215K loss). `slippageBp` is a
// base `Long` field of `Amm::SwapContext` (lowered from `SwapParams.slippage_bp`,
// or reducer-derived from min_out↔expected), so this judges with NO enrichment
// (sv = COV). 300 bp (3%) is the warn threshold here.
@id("swap-slippage-high-warn")
@severity("warn")
@reason("This swap allows a very wide slippage band — an easy target for sandwich MEV")
forbid(principal, action == Amm::Action::"Swap", resource)
when { context.slippageBp > 300 };

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: GEN-09 (blind / opaque signature).
//
// Warn whenever an action could not be decoded by any manifest and therefore
// surfaces as `Core::Action::"Unknown"` (opaque EIP-712, raw `eth_sign`, or
// calldata no adapter matched). Signature-phishing leans on exactly these
// undecodable requests, so the wallet should flag them for a human look.
//
// This is a pure action-shape policy (Aggregator type 8 — Decode
// Introspection): the verdict depends only on the decoded action's *identity*,
// not on any enriched fact. The manifest therefore declares no `policy_rpc`
// calls and no `custom_context`.
@id("unknown-blind-sign-warning")
@severity("warn")
forbid(principal, action == Core::Action::"Unknown", resource);

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: GEN-01 (unlimited / over-balance
// ERC20 approval to a non-allowlisted spender).
//
// An `approve(spender, amount)` with `amount == U256::MAX` (or an amount far
// exceeding the wallet's balance) hands `spender` an open-ended claim on the
// token — the canonical token-drain primitive. `amount` is a raw U256 hex
// String on the base context, so "unlimited" CANNOT be tested in Cedar
// directly; it arrives as the enriched Bool `approvalIsUnlimited`, projected
// into `context.custom` by the manifest's `approval.unlimited_over_balance`
// policy_rpc call (see manifest.json). `custom` is optional, so the guard
// `has`-checks the path before reading it.
//
// `approvalAmountOverBalance` (decimal, approve-amount / available-balance) is
// also projected for over-balance scoring; this slice keys the deny on the
// unlimited flag, leaving the over-balance threshold to a later increment.
//
// The allowlist (spenders for whom an unlimited approval is expected, e.g. the
// canonical Permit2 contract) is user configuration; for this slice it is
// inlined as a Cedar set literal (design proposal F#2 — personalized supply via
// enrichment/Set<String> custom field is a later increment). Addresses are
// lowercase hex; the sample entry below is the canonical Permit2 contract.
@id("unlimited-approval-deny")
@severity("deny")
forbid(principal, action == Token::Action::"Erc20Approve", resource)
when {
  context has custom
  && context.custom has approvalIsUnlimited
  && context.custom.approvalIsUnlimited
  && !(["0x000000000022d473030f116ddee9f6b43ac78ba3"].contains(context.spender))
};

// pasu default v2 policy — explorer id: H3 / VALUE (personal allow/deny
// list for tokens / contracts).
//
// Personal-trading (TradFi pre-trade) family. Deny an AMM swap whose `recipient`
// (the address that will receive the bought tokens) is on the user's personal
// denylist. This is the canonical Set-Membership control (Aggregator type 5):
// the user keeps a local "never route to / never trade these" list.
//
// sv = COV today (per tradfi mapping §H3): no enrichment, no external feed. The
// denylist is LOCAL user config and — per the team decision recorded in the
// coverage doc — is kept as a Cedar `Set<String>` LITERAL for now (a future
// local handler→Bool projection is the personalized-supply increment, mirroring
// the GEN-01 allowlist literal). Because the set is a literal, this manifest
// declares NO `policy_rpc` and NO `custom_context` — like `swap-slippage-high-warn`.
//
// CHOICE: we denylist on `context.recipient` (a base `String` field of
// `Amm::SwapContext`, always present) rather than on `context.tokenOut`. The
// token identity lives at `context.tokenOut.key.address`, which is an OPTIONAL
// nested field (`address?`) and would require chained `has`-guards to read in
// Cedar; the `recipient` String is non-optional and tests cleanly. A token
// denylist is the symmetric variant once a `tokenOutAddress` projection (or the
// nested-`has` form) is wired — see the coverage doc's H3 note. Addresses are
// lowercase hex; the sample entries below are placeholders.
@id("values-recipient-denylist-deny")
@severity("deny")
@reason("This swap routes to an address on your personal denylist")
forbid(principal, action == Amm::Action::"Swap", resource)
when {
  ["0x000000000000000000000000000000000000dead",
   "0x00000000000000000000000000000000deadbeef"].contains(context.recipient)
};
